BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 81.6 600 Td (Chapter 5: Filming Your First Video) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Your first video does not need to be perfect. It needs to exist.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Choose a topic you know well so you can speak confidently without extensive prep.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Write a simple outline with three to five main points you want to cover.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Set up your filming space with good lighting and minimal background distractions.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Frame yourself from the chest up with your eyes in the upper third of the frame.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Look directly at the camera lens, not the screen, to create eye contact with viewers.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Speak to one imaginary person, not an audience. This creates natural conversation.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (If you make a mistake, pause and re-say the sentence. Edit it out later.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Keep your first video between five and ten minutes. Do not over-explain.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Film a short intro, deliver your content, and end with a clear call to action.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Record more footage than you need. You can always cut in editing.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Hit record and start talking. The hardest part is pressing the button.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 213.6 30 Td (5) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
